| i | arr\[i] | max | second\_max | Why?                                         |
| - | ------- | --- | ----------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| 0 | 12      | 12  | INT\_MIN    | First number, becomes `max`                  |
| 1 | 35      | 35  | 12          | New biggest â†’ update both                    |
| 2 | 1       | 35  | 12          | Smaller than both â†’ no change                |
| 3 | 10      | 35  | 12          | Smaller than both â†’ no change                |
| 4 | 34      | 35  | 34          | Smaller than `max`, bigger than `second_max` |
| 5 | 1       | 35  | 34          | No change                                    |

so print- 34

    So whatâ€™s the "problem-solving strategy" here?

    You're tracking two values dynamically

    The idea is to update your values only when necessary

    You're avoiding brute-force methods like sorting or nested loops

    It's a single-pass, stateful solution

ðŸ“¦ This becomes a general technique:
    When asked to find â€œtop 2â€, â€œmin and second minâ€, â€œkth largestâ€ â€” you can extend this style.

